quran[25]{c,v,t}:
  78,31,"Indeed, for the mindful<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a><i class=""s"">(of God) </i>there is triumph:"
  78,32,"Gardens<i class=""s"">(of Paradise) </i>and vineyards;"
  78,33,"and high-class spouses, well-matched;"
  78,34,"and overflowing cups."
  78,35,"They hear therein neither idle talk nor lies—"
  78,36,"a repayment from your<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>Lord, a measured gift,"
  78,37,"(from)<span class=""h"">the Lord<sup foot_note=""81424"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span>of the heavens and the earth and everything between them,<i class=""s"">(from) </i>the All-Merciful. They have no authority from Him to speak"
  78,38,"on the day when the Spirit and the angels line up in ranks, not speaking—except whomever the All-Merciful has permitted and who has said what is right."
  78,39,"That is the True Day. So whoever wills, let him take a route to return to his Lord."
  78,40,"Indeed, We have warned you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>of a near punishment—the day when a person looks at what his hands have put forth, and the denier says, “If only I were dust!”"
  79,1,"By those who snatch violently{1}.",footnotes:1:Al-Alousi and other exegetes mentioned that these are angels snatching the souls of the disbelievers.
  79,2,"By those who remove gently."
  79,3,"By those who glide smoothly,"
  79,4,"and by those who race swiftly,"
  79,5,"and by those who regulate matters—"
  79,6,"on the day when the Quake quakes"
  79,7,"and is followed by the Successor,"
  79,8,"hearts on that day are pounding,"
  79,9,"their sight<i class=""s"">(s) </i><i class=""s"">(subdued) </i>in reverence."
  79,10,"They say, “<span class=""h"">Can it be<sup foot_note=""81426"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span><span class=""h"">that we will really</span>be restored to the original condition?"
  79,11,"<span class=""h"">Can that be<sup foot_note=""81427"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span><span class=""h"">when we have</span>become <span class=""h"">worn</span><span class=""h"">out<sup foot_note=""81428"" class=""qiraat"">2</sup> </span>bones?”"
  79,12,"They said{1}, “This is a losing return.”",footnotes:1:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense, this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  79,13,"Yet, indeed, it is nothing but a single nudge,"
  79,14,"and they are all awake."
  79,15,"Has the story of Moses reached you<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>?"
